# MyRoadClub App — Project Notes

## Brand (myroadclub.com)

- **Look**: Colors align with [myroadclub.com](https://myroadclub.com/) — primary **#00a0e3**, cyan **#39c8df**, text **#232323**, borders **#e6e6e6** (see `:root` in `app/globals.css`).
- **Logo**: Header uses `https://myroadclub.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/IMG_7802-300x300.png` (`app/page.tsx`).
- **Type**: **Roboto** via `next/font` in `app/layout.tsx`.
- **My Account / auth**: The app signs members in through the WordPress `/wp-json/jwt-auth/v1/token` endpoint. The dedicated login page stores `wp_token` in `localStorage` when **Remember me** is selected (the default) or `sessionStorage` when it is cleared; the account slide-over sign-in stores it in `localStorage`. These browser Web Storage tokens are script-accessible bearer credentials, not HttpOnly cookies, and must not be described as protected from client-side script access.

## Roadside Assistance (request form + GPS + call)

- **UI**: Home **Roadside Assistance** section uses **tabs**: **Got a ticket?**, **Roadside Assistance** (full request form), **Plan a Trip** (trip planning area loads `https://myroadclub.com`; presented like the rest of the app, no extra browser-style chrome). Default tab is **Got a ticket?**
- **Roadside form** (second tab): **Roadside Assistance Request** with: quick **service type** tiles (Jump Start, Flat Tire, Fuel Delivery, Lockout, Winch-out, Towing, Battery, Other), service details, customer info (with **Member?** toggle and optional account fields), vehicle fields, **Get current GPS location** with Google Maps embed + optional address fields filled via **OpenStreetMap Nominatim** reverse geocode (browser `fetch`), towing **drop-off** block when **Towing** is selected, additional options, and **Submit service request**.
- **GPS**: High-accuracy `navigator.geolocation`; maps use shared helpers in `lib/maps.ts` (`googleMapsEmbedUrl` / `googleMapsUrl`).
- **Call**: **Call dispatch now** uses `tel:` with `NEXT_PUBLIC_ROADSIDE_PHONE` (default placeholder until set in `.env.local`).
- **Got a ticket?**: Optional **photo/PDF upload** (JPEG, PNG, and PDF; up to 10 files, 10 MB each, 50 MB combined) with image thumbnails and filename list.
- **Submit**: Both forms submit to the authenticated WordPress request API through `lib/wp-requests.ts`, await HTTP 201 before showing success, display the returned reference, preserve form state after failures, and show actionable auth/validation/size/network/server errors.
- **Persistence**: The `wordpress/myroadclub-requests/` plugin exposes authenticated POST endpoints for both forms, stores pending private WordPress request records authored by the signed-in member, and is the canonical owner of the request post types, registered meta schema, server-side validation, persistence, and admin presentation. Ticket JPEG/PNG/PDF files are stored as linked WordPress Media Library attachments.
- **Success**: The server response controls success; the client only shows success after an HTTP 201 response with a valid `RA-...` or `TK-...` reference.
- **Config**: Production builds use `.env.production.local`; `NEXT_PUBLIC_WORDPRESS_URL` selects the WordPress REST origin and is embedded at build time; dispatch phone is currently `+6654551559`.

## Member profile and request autofill

- **API**: The WordPress plugin exposes authenticated `GET` and `PATCH` requests at `/wp-json/myroadclub/v1/member-profile`. WordPress derives the target user from the member JWT; callers cannot select another user.
- **Profile page**: Protected `/profile` lets members edit first name, last name, display name, email, and phone. Username and membership ID are displayed read-only.
- **Field sources**: WordPress core owns names, display name, and email. Phone reads canonical `mrc_phone` when that key exists, otherwise falls back to `billing_phone` then `phone`; updates write `mrc_phone` and synchronize an existing `billing_phone`. Membership ID reads the first non-empty value from `mrc_membership_id`, `membership_id`, then `membership_number`, and is never member-editable.
- **Autofill**: Ticket requests prefill first name, last name, phone, and email. Roadside requests also prefill account/display name and membership ID and mark the requester as a member. Defaults apply once per form mount and only to empty fields, so delayed profile loads and profile-update events do not overwrite member-entered request data.
- **Shared state**: `lib/wp-profile.ts` owns authenticated profile requests, safe errors, caching, and update events. A successful profile save refreshes the cache; failed profile loads leave request fields editable.

## Other URLs

- **Plan a Trip (tab)**: `https://myroadclub.com` — shown in-app; remote site may restrict embedding.
- **Travel deals**: `https://limitless-advantage.globaltravel.com/` (not linked on the current home screen).
- **Main site**: `NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL` or https://myroadclub.com if you add links elsewhere.

## Production deployment

- **URL / VPS**: `https://app.myroadclub.com` on `64.225.43.219`.
- **Architecture**: Next.js static export served directly by Nginx; no Node.js production process.
- **Deploy order**: Install, configure, activate, and verify the WordPress request plugin (including the member-profile GET/PATCH API) first; only then build the app on the Mac with `NEXT_PUBLIC_WORDPRESS_URL=https://myroadclub.com` and run `SSH_TARGET=deploy@64.225.43.219 ./scripts/deploy-static.sh`.
- **WordPress server**: PHP-FPM and Nginx must allow the documented multipart upload limits, Nginx must forward the `Authorization` header, production CORS permits `https://app.myroadclub.com`, and optional local browser testing uses the exact `MRC_REQUESTS_DEV_ORIGIN` configured in `wp-config.php`.
- **Deploy script**: The static deployment script uses an owner-checked remote lock and rolls back failures before completion.
- **Releases**: `/var/www/app.myroadclub.com/releases`; Nginx serves the atomic `current` symlink and retains five releases.
- **TLS**: Let's Encrypt certificate with automatic renewal and the versioned Nginx reload hook in `ops/certbot/deploy-hooks`; HTTP redirects to HTTPS.
- **Runbook**: See `docs/deployment.md`.

